06232nam a22007815i 9789400604421DE-B159720240306015011.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97894006044217 a10.1515/97894006044212doi  a(DE-B1597)641170  a(OCoLC)1390923328  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aHIS0360002bisacsh04a327.73054qOCoLC223/eng/2023112004aThe United States and South Asia from the Age of Empire to Decolonization :bA History of Entanglements /ced. by Nico Slate, Harald Fischer-Tiné. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGlobal Connections: Routes and Roots ;v500tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction: Religion, Politics, and Development ― Mapping the Sites and Domains of Indo-American Exchange, c. 1850–1970 -- tPart I: Religion and Culture -- tChapter 1. A Gold Rush, Steamships, and Blackface : The New York Serenaders in San Francisco and India, early-1850s. -- tChapter 2. The Sepoy Rebellion and American Global Ambition -- tChapter 3. Fakir : How a Word from India Moved Through American Popular Culture for Nearly a Century -- tPart II: Missionaries and Political Activists -- tChapter 4. American Humanitarianism in Colonial South Asia : The Famine Relief of the American Marathi Mission in Bombay, 1896–1900 -- tChapter 5. ‘One fifth of the world’s boyhood’ : American ‘Boyology’ and the YMCA’s work with early adolescents in India (c. 1900–1950) -- tChapter 6. Taraknath Das: Race and Citizenship between India and the U.S.A. -- tChapter 7. Socialism, Nonviolence, and Civil Rights : The American Journeys of Rammanohar Lohia -- tPart III: Social Sciences, Development Initiatives & Technocracy -- tChapter 8. Constructing an Indian Sociology : ‘Karimpur’, U.S. Area Studies and Cold War Social Science -- tChapter 9. The Development of Uttar Pradesh Agricultural University -- tChapter 10. The Bankura Horse as Development Object : Women’s Work, Indo-American Exchanges, and the Global Handicraft Trade -- tAfterword -- tBibliography -- tAbout the Authors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe contributions assembled in this volume present cutting-edge research that examines the network of Indo-American interconnections over a wider time frame. The case studies stretch into the early decades of the American republic hinting at a longer history of mutual influence and exchange, beyond the registers of ‘the American century’ of globalization. By bringing together academics working across disciplines ranging from history to cultural and literary studies, comparative religion, political science and sociology, this volume thus foregrounds and historicizes the complex, multi-sited, polyvalent nature of the Indo-US encounter. At the same time, the book explore the possibilities of methodologically engaging with established categories—such as the nation, the imperial and Empire—and test alternative typologies to better understand this encounter. Taken together, our authors reconstruct the myriad ways in which Americans and Indians have engaged with each other through trade, diplomacy, intellectual comradeship, missionary evangelism and revolutionary fervor.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDecolonizationzSouth AsiaxHistoryy20th century. 4aContemporary History. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aInternational Relations. 4aSouth Asia. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  aUS, India, Relation, Religion, Politics, Development.1 aBose, Neilesh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeslippe, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat